---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
---

<DocsLayout
	title="migrate skill"
	description="The migrate skill converts an existing project's styling onto Tideway without changing how it looks."
	active="migrate"
>
	<article class="doc">
		<p class="doc__eyebrow">Skill</p>
		<h1 class="doc__title">migrate</h1>
		<p class="doc__lead">
			Converts an existing project — Tailwind, plain CSS, or a CSS-in-JS setup — onto Tideway's
			tokens and BEM. The rendered UI is the fixed point: the CSS underneath changes, the result
			doesn't.
		</p>

		<section class="doc__section">
			<h2 class="doc__section-title">How it works</h2>
			<div class="doc__list">
				<p class="doc__item">
					Reads the <a class="doc__link" href="/docs/style">style</a> skill first, so it knows the exact
					tokens and BEM rules it's migrating onto.
				</p>
				<p class="doc__item">
					Identifies the source system and follows a source-specific mapping. Tailwind is supported
					today; other sources fall back to a hand-mapping workflow.
				</p>
				<p class="doc__item">
					Works incrementally — one component at a time, verifying the rendered result matches before
					moving on.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="doc__section">
			<h2 class="doc__section-title">Migrating from Tailwind</h2>
			<p class="doc__text">
				Tideway's scales are the same scales Tailwind uses, so most utilities map one-to-one to a
				token — <code class="doc__code">p-6</code> becomes
				<code class="doc__code">padding: var(--space-6)</code>,
				<code class="doc__code">bg-blue-500</code> becomes
				<code class="doc__code">background-color: var(--color-blue-500)</code>. The real work is
				regrouping utilities into BEM classes, not recomputing values.
			</p>
		</section>
	</article>
</DocsLayout>
